{"action": "input", "code": "def draw_yellow_lines_from_endpoints_to_edge(input_grid: np.ndarray, endpoints: Tuple[Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int]], direction: Tuple[int, int]) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes in a numpy array as input_grid, the two endpoints of the line which is in black and on the one side of the rectangle of four points,\n    and the direction in which the rectangle's side has the two endpoints. It draws yellow lines from the two endpoints and pixels between them to the edge of grid in the direction.\n    \n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array representing the input grid\n    endpoints: A tuple containing two tuples, each representing the x and y coordinates of an endpoint of the line.\n    direction: A tuple containing two integers representing the direction in which the rectangle's side has the two endpoints.\n    \n    Returns:\n    A numpy array with yellow lines drawn from the two endpoints and pixels between them to the edge of grid in the direction.\n    \"\"\"\n    rows, cols = input_grid.shape\n    x0, y0 = endpoints[0]\n    x1, y1 = endpoints[1]\n    while x0 >= 0 and x0 < cols and (y0 >= 0) and (y0 < rows):\n        input_grid[y0][x0] = yellow\n        if x0 == x1 and y0 == y1:\n            break\n        x0 += direction[0]\n        y0 += direction[1]\n    return input_grid\ndef get_direction(x0: int, x1: int, y0: int, y1: int, input_grid: np.ndarray, endpoints: Tuple[Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int]]) -> Tuple[int, int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes in the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates where the pixel is not black, the input grid,\n    and the two endpoints of the line which is in black and on the one side of the rectangle of four points.\n    It returns the direction in which the rectangle's side has the two endpoints.\n    \n    Args:\n    x0: An integer representing the minimum x coordinate where the pixel is not black.\n    x1: An integer representing the maximum x coordinate where the pixel is not black.\n    y0: An integer representing the minimum y coordinate where the pixel is not black.\n    y1: An integer representing the maximum y coordinate where the pixel is not black.\n    input_grid: A numpy array representing the input grid\n    endpoints: A tuple containing two tuples, each representing the x and y coordinates of an endpoint of the line.\n    \n    Returns:\n    A tuple containing two integers representing the direction in which the rectangle's side has the two endpoints.\n    \"\"\"\n    if endpoints[0][0] == x0:\n        return (1, 0)\n    elif endpoints[0][0] == x1:\n        return (-1, 0)\n    elif endpoints[0][1] == y0:\n        return (0, 1)\n    elif endpoints[0][1] == y1:\n        return (0, -1)\n    else:\n        raise ValueError('Invalid endpoints')\ndef main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    x0, x1, y0, y1 = get_min_max_coordinates(input_grid)\n    endpoints = get_endpoints(x0, x1, y0, y1, input_grid)\n    direction = get_direction(x0, x1, y0, y1, input_grid, endpoints)\n    output_grid = change_color_of_pixels_inside_rectangle_with_black(input_grid, x0, x1, y0, y1)\n    output_grid = draw_yellow_lines_from_endpoints_to_edge(output_grid, endpoints, direction)\n    output_grid = 'draw yellow diagonal lines from the two endpoints going to the edge of the grid'(output_grid)\n    return output_grid\ndef change_color_of_pixels_inside_rectangle_with_black(input_grid: np.ndarray, x0: int, x1: int, y0: int, y1: int) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes in a numpy array as input_grid and the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates where the pixel is not black.\n    It changes the color of all the pixels inside the rectangle with black.\n    \n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array representing the input grid\n    x0: An integer representing the minimum x coordinate where the pixel is not black.\n    x1: An integer representing the maximum x coordinate where the pixel is not black.\n    y0: An integer representing the minimum y coordinate where the pixel is not black.\n    y1: An integer representing the maximum y coordinate where the pixel is not black.\n    \n    Returns:\n    A numpy array with the color of all the pixels inside the rectangle with black changed.\n    \"\"\"\n    for i in range(y0 + 1, y1):\n        for j in range(x0 + 1, x1):\n            input_grid[i][j] = yellow\n    return input_grid\ndef get_endpoints(x0: int, x1: int, y0: int, y1: int, input_grid: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int]]:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes in the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates where the pixel is not black and the input grid.\n    It returns the two endpoints of the line which is in black and on the one side of the rectangle of four points.\n    \n    Args:\n    x0: An integer representing the minimum x coordinate where the pixel is not black.\n    x1: An integer representing the maximum x coordinate where the pixel is not black.\n    y0: An integer representing the minimum y coordinate where the pixel is not black.\n    y1: An integer representing the maximum y coordinate where the pixel is not black.\n    input_grid: A numpy array representing the input grid\n    \n    Returns:\n    A tuple containing two tuples, each representing the x and y coordinates of an endpoint of the line.\n    \"\"\"\n    endpoints = []\n    for i in range(y0, y1 + 1):\n        if input_grid[i][x0] == black:\n            endpoints.append((x0, i))\n            break\n        elif input_grid[i][x1] == black:\n            endpoints.append((x1, i))\n            break\n    return tuple(endpoints)\ndef get_min_max_coordinates(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[int, int, int, int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes in a numpy array as input_grid and returns the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates\n    where the pixel is not black.\n    \n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array representing the input grid\n    \n    Returns:\n    A tuple containing the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates where the pixel is not black.\n    \"\"\"\n    rows, cols = input_grid.shape\n    x0, y0 = (cols, rows)\n    x1, y1 = (-1, -1)\n    for i in range(rows):\n        for j in range(cols):\n            if input_grid[i][j] != black:\n                x0 = min(x0, j)\n                y0 = min(y0, i)\n                x1 = max(x1, j)\n                y1 = max(y1, i)\n    return (x0, x1, y0, y1)", "user_code": "def main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n  (x0, x1, y0, y1) = `get min/max x/y of the locations where the pixel is not in black`(input_grid)\n  endpoints = `get the two endpoints of the line which is in black and on the one side of the rectange of four points`(x0,x1,y0,y1,input_grid)\n  direction = `get the direction in which the rectangle's side has the two endpoints`(x0,x1,y0,y1,input_grid, endpoints)\n  output_grid = `change the color of all the pixels inside the rectangle with black`(input_grid, x0, x1, y0, y1)\n  output_grid = `draw yellow lines from the two endpoints and pixels between them to the edge of grid in the direction`(output_grid, endpoints, direction)\n  output_grid = 'draw yellow diagonal lines from the two endpoints going to the edge of the grid'(output_grid)\n  return output_grid\n", "gpt_code": "def draw_yellow_lines_from_endpoints_to_edge(input_grid: np.ndarray, endpoints: Tuple[Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int]], direction: Tuple[int, int]) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes in a numpy array as input_grid, the two endpoints of the line which is in black and on the one side of the rectangle of four points,\n    and the direction in which the rectangle's side has the two endpoints. It draws yellow lines from the two endpoints and pixels between them to the edge of grid in the direction.\n    \n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array representing the input grid\n    endpoints: A tuple containing two tuples, each representing the x and y coordinates of an endpoint of the line.\n    direction: A tuple containing two integers representing the direction in which the rectangle's side has the two endpoints.\n    \n    Returns:\n    A numpy array with yellow lines drawn from the two endpoints and pixels between them to the edge of grid in the direction.\n    \"\"\"\n    rows, cols = input_grid.shape\n    x0, y0 = endpoints[0]\n    x1, y1 = endpoints[1]\n    while x0 >= 0 and x0 < cols and (y0 >= 0) and (y0 < rows):\n        input_grid[y0][x0] = yellow\n        if x0 == x1 and y0 == y1:\n            break\n        x0 += direction[0]\n        y0 += direction[1]\n    return input_grid\ndef get_direction(x0: int, x1: int, y0: int, y1: int, input_grid: np.ndarray, endpoints: Tuple[Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int]]) -> Tuple[int, int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes in the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates where the pixel is not black, the input grid,\n    and the two endpoints of the line which is in black and on the one side of the rectangle of four points.\n    It returns the direction in which the rectangle's side has the two endpoints.\n    \n    Args:\n    x0: An integer representing the minimum x coordinate where the pixel is not black.\n    x1: An integer representing the maximum x coordinate where the pixel is not black.\n    y0: An integer representing the minimum y coordinate where the pixel is not black.\n    y1: An integer representing the maximum y coordinate where the pixel is not black.\n    input_grid: A numpy array representing the input grid\n    endpoints: A tuple containing two tuples, each representing the x and y coordinates of an endpoint of the line.\n    \n    Returns:\n    A tuple containing two integers representing the direction in which the rectangle's side has the two endpoints.\n    \"\"\"\n    if endpoints[0][0] == x0:\n        return (1, 0)\n    elif endpoints[0][0] == x1:\n        return (-1, 0)\n    elif endpoints[0][1] == y0:\n        return (0, 1)\n    elif endpoints[0][1] == y1:\n        return (0, -1)\n    else:\n        raise ValueError('Invalid endpoints')\ndef change_color_of_pixels_inside_rectangle_with_black(input_grid: np.ndarray, x0: int, x1: int, y0: int, y1: int) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes in a numpy array as input_grid and the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates where the pixel is not black.\n    It changes the color of all the pixels inside the rectangle with black.\n    \n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array representing the input grid\n    x0: An integer representing the minimum x coordinate where the pixel is not black.\n    x1: An integer representing the maximum x coordinate where the pixel is not black.\n    y0: An integer representing the minimum y coordinate where the pixel is not black.\n    y1: An integer representing the maximum y coordinate where the pixel is not black.\n    \n    Returns:\n    A numpy array with the color of all the pixels inside the rectangle with black changed.\n    \"\"\"\n    for i in range(y0 + 1, y1):\n        for j in range(x0 + 1, x1):\n            input_grid[i][j] = yellow\n    return input_grid\ndef get_endpoints(x0: int, x1: int, y0: int, y1: int, input_grid: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int]]:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes in the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates where the pixel is not black and the input grid.\n    It returns the two endpoints of the line which is in black and on the one side of the rectangle of four points.\n    \n    Args:\n    x0: An integer representing the minimum x coordinate where the pixel is not black.\n    x1: An integer representing the maximum x coordinate where the pixel is not black.\n    y0: An integer representing the minimum y coordinate where the pixel is not black.\n    y1: An integer representing the maximum y coordinate where the pixel is not black.\n    input_grid: A numpy array representing the input grid\n    \n    Returns:\n    A tuple containing two tuples, each representing the x and y coordinates of an endpoint of the line.\n    \"\"\"\n    endpoints = []\n    for i in range(y0, y1 + 1):\n        if input_grid[i][x0] == black:\n            endpoints.append((x0, i))\n            break\n        elif input_grid[i][x1] == black:\n            endpoints.append((x1, i))\n            break\n    return tuple(endpoints)\ndef get_min_max_coordinates(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[int, int, int, int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes in a numpy array as input_grid and returns the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates\n    where the pixel is not black.\n    \n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array representing the input grid\n    \n    Returns:\n    A tuple containing the minimum and maximum x and y coordinates where the pixel is not black.\n    \"\"\"\n    rows, cols = input_grid.shape\n    x0, y0 = (cols, rows)\n    x1, y1 = (-1, -1)\n    for i in range(rows):\n        for j in range(cols):\n            if input_grid[i][j] != black:\n                x0 = min(x0, j)\n                y0 = min(y0, i)\n                x1 = max(x1, j)\n                y1 = max(y1, i)\n    return (x0, x1, y0, y1)", "holes": {"draw_yellow_lines_from_endpoints_to_edge": "draw yellow lines from the two endpoints and pixels between them to the edge of grid in the direction", "get_direction": "get the direction in which the rectangle's side has the two endpoints", "change_color_of_pixels_inside_rectangle_with_black": "change the color of all the pixels inside the rectangle with black", "get_endpoints": "get the two endpoints of the line which is in black and on the one side of the rectange of four points", "get_min_max_coordinates": "get min/max x/y of the locations where the pixel is not in black"}}
